rhouse (project lead, Efficio). Andrew has been responsive but passive: he confirmed on 13 May 2026 'no update on RFP yet' and on 2 Jul 2026 (via the deal owner's outreach) 'nothing required from Zycus team at this stage' (SF Next_Step__c, 13 May 2026, 2 Jul 2026). Andrew is not an advocate; he is a gatekeeper executing a vendor-agnostic RFP process. When Zycus Alliances attempted to influence Efficio on 20 Mar 2026, Efficio responded 'not interested, Efficio are vendor agnostic' (SF Next_Step__c, 20 Mar 2026). Inside PIF, the Contact Roles list four individuals (Sofian Ouahchi, Abdullah Almanyah, Lujain Mosaeb, Supplier Relationship Management generic role), but none have been engaged on an Avoma call or shown advocacy. The Economic Buyer (Abdulaziz Alsuwailem, SVP) is identified but unengaged. The lack of a champion 28 days from close in a six-vendor bake-off is fatal: Zycus has no one inside PIF pushing for Zycus, no visibility into the scoring or deliberations, and no political leverage. Competitors with direct PIF relationships will have a structural advantage. The immediate move is twofold: (1) secure the EB meeting and convert Alsuwailem or a direct report into an active sponsor, and (2) identify a coach inside PIF who can provide intelligence on the RFP status and competitive positioning. Without a champion, the deal is passive and reactive."}, "competition": {"status": "confirmed", "sources": ["SF Competitors__c", "SF Next_Step__c 8 Oct 2025", "SF Next_Step__c 20 Mar 2026"], "narrative": "PIF's RFP includes six named vendors: SAP Ariba, GEP Worldwide, Coupa, iValua, JAGGAER, and 'Others' (SF Competitors__c). SAP Ariba is the primary competitor given their dominant Middle East presence, existing KSA hosting infrastructure, and deep penetration in sovereign and enterprise accounts across the Gulf. GEP Worldwide has a strong Middle East consulting and software footprint. The 8 Oct 2025 meeting noted the RFP will 'involve whole S2P market', confirming this is a